passages.text: Consumer | Global Retailing, Softlines & Luxury Brands
Gap Inc. GAP| \(21.73\) Outperform|Target Price/Base Cases \(20.00(from\) 24.00) Earnings Report
Company StatisticsMarket Capitalization (M)$7,99152-Week Range$16.99 - $29.29
1 Year Price History

Bottom Line: 2Q EPS at \(0.57 beat Street\) 0.55 (EVRe \(0.53) on mixed sales (SSS +1% vs. Street +2%; EVRe +1%), likely meeting market expectations in today's backdrop. We're impressed with the brand momentum across the majority of the portfolio (Old Navy 2Q SSS +2%, Gap +4%, Banana Republic +4%). That said, our hunch is that—vs 90 days ago—GAP has decided to add price increases to its tariff mitigation plan (after previously taking a hard stance on protecting the value equation)—which adds some risk to the model going forward. Relative to other retailers in our space, GAP has somewhat less conservative sales deceleration assumptions in 2H. And unlike Specialty Apparel peers, GAP didn't clearly diagnose the potential for tariffs to wrap around into 1H26. We're encouraged by the brand momentum, and GAP noted that 2025 should be the bottom on margins (likely with 1H26 lower, then 2H26 higher to bring the full year above 2025), but we'd hoped for more details on the strategy on the call after a much more conservative outlook 90 days ago.

GM Cadence Likely the Focus Today: While GAP's brands have top line momentum, we think the key focus revolves around GAP's back half GM guidance, which embeds 3Q GM down - 150bp to - 170bp (from down - 130bp in 2Q), then improving to down only - 40bp to - 100bp in 4Q (a - 90bp sequential improvement at the midpoint) despite a similar tariff impact in both. We think there are three inputs driving the implied 4Q improvement:
Stronger 4Q Top Line: We think GAP is attributing part of the 4Q GM acceleration to sequential improvement in the top line (though implied 4Q guide only implies a slight acceleration).
Freight leverage accelerates in 4Q vs. 3Q (particularly from less air freight usage assumed vs 4Q24) We model no air freight impact in 3Q and a 30bp of leverage in 4Q.
Cotton should provide a meaningful benefit in 4Q. We model +10bp of AUC benefit in 3Q accelerating to +40bp in 4Q.

Price Increases Coming? Despite GAP's blended tariff rate likely doubling since the 1Q call, the mitigated tariff impact to 2025 only increased to \(\) 150m\(to\) \ \(175m\) (from \(\) 100m\(to\) \ \(150m\) prior). Our concern is GAP was clear about caution related to taking price (particularly at Old Navy) on the 1Q call, but was a little less clear about protecting value at all costs today. We think GAP has added

some price increases, and while that may very well work (we simply didn't think GAP would be the odd- man out with the industry starting to look to new pricing equilibria), we would've liked more detail around the plan on the call. Our new Target Multiple of 10x (from 11x prior) reflects incremental risk surrounding price increases for the value chain.

Where We Stand on the Stock: Stepping back, we still see value here. GAP was clear today that the 2025 EBIT margin guide for \(6.7\%\) to \(7.0\%\) was the floor on margins and should improve next year. Three of the brands have better heat today (and Athleta will take some time, but is relatively stable). Old Navy comps of \(+2\%\) (lapping \(+5\%\) last year) suggest the brand can return to consistent +LSD% comps, which we think could help bridge the brand from what are likely segment margins at just +HSD% today back to historical levels near \(15\%\) (which would add \(+100bp\) to corporate margins, and we suspect meaningful progress on ON margins next year is a key offset to tariffs in 2026). Bottom line, we think GAP can deliver \(+8\%\) EPS growth next year—making its current 9.8x P/E on our new 2026 number reasonable.

2Q by the Numbers: EPS of \(\) 0.57\(beat Street\) \ \(0.55\) (EVRe \(\) 0.53)\(on SSS + 1\%\) (Street \(+2.0\%\) ; EVRe \(+1.4\%\) ) with Old Navy \(+2\%\) (Street \(+2.4\%\) ; EVRe \(+2.0\%\) ), Gap \(+4\%\) (Street/EVRe \(+4.0\%\) ), and Banana Republic \(+4\%\) (Street \(+0.3\%\) ; EVRe \(+1.0\%\) ). GM was \(41.2\%\) (slightly below Street/EVRe \(41.9\%\) ) and OpEx was \(33.4\%\) of sales (Street \(34.5\%\) ; EVRe \(34.6\%\) ) though had 1x benefits from investments shifting into 3Q.

Valuation: Raise our Target Price to \(\) 25\(based on 10x our 2027E EPS estimate (from\) \ \(24\) on 11x 2026E prior). We're rolling our Target Price forward to be based off of 2027 (from 2026 prior) and lowering our multiple to 10x (from 11x prior) to reflect slightly increased risk to the model on potential incoming price increases.

Evercore ISI's recommendations are based on a stock's total forecasted return over the next 12 months. Total forecasted return is equal to the expected percentage price return plus gross dividend yield. We divide our stocks under coverage into three primary ratings categories, with the following return guidelines:

Outperform- the total forecasted return is expected to be greater than the expected total return of the analyst's coverage sector. In Line- the total forecasted return is expected to be in line with the expected total return of the analyst's coverage sector. Underperform- the total forecasted return is expected to be less than the expected total return of the analyst's coverage sector. Coverage Suspended- the rating and target price have been removed pursuant to Evercore ISI policy when Evercore is acting in an advisory capacity in a merger or strategic transaction involving this company and in certain other circumstances. Rating Suspended- Evercore ISI has suspended the rating and target price for this stock because there is not sufficient fundamental basis for determining, or there are legal, regulatory or policy constraints around publishing, a rating or target price. The previous rating and target price, if any, are no longer in effect for this company and should not be relied upon.
Prior to October 10, 2015, the "Coverage Suspended" and "Rating Suspended" categories were included in the category "Suspended."

FINRA requires that members who use a ratings system with terms other than "Buy," "Hold/Neutral" and "Sell" to equate their own ratings to these categories. For this purpose, and in the Evercore ISI ratings distribution below, our Outperform, In Line, and Underperform ratings can be equated to Buy, Hold and Sell, respectively.
